          "body": "The tribal allotments are interrupted at their precise midpoint by the sacred district (vv. 8-22), and the interruption is structural theology. Seven tribes lie north of the district (Dan, Asher, Naphtali, Manasseh, Ephraim, Reuben, Judah); five lie south (Benjamin, Simeon, Issachar, Zebulun, Gad). The sacred district itself is internally layered: the innermost zone belongs to the Zadokite priests and contains the sanctuary (vv. 10-12); immediately adjacent is the Levitical zone (v.13); surrounding these is the common-use zone with the city at its center (vv. 15-19); and flanking the entire sacred rectangle are the lands of the prince (vv. 21-22). The concentric arrangement is not architectural preference — it is a moral and theological map. Proximity to the sanctuary corresponds to fidelity to God's charge. The Zadokites, who 'kept My charge' and 'did not go astray when the sons of Israel went astray' (v.11), receive the holiest land. The Levites, who went astray with Israel, receive land adjacent but not innermost. Holiness radiates outward from the sanctuary, and faithfulness determines how close each group stands to the source."
