        "body": "The city's gate-catalog (vv. 30-34) is architecturally brief but theologically dense. Four sides, three gates each, twelve names — the entire covenant community mapped onto the city's perimeter. The gates are called *totsaot* (exits/outlets, v.30) rather than entrances — the city opens outward, not only inward. Access is bidirectional; the restored community moves through gates, not past locked walls.\n\nThe gate-list differs from the tribal allotment-list in two instructive ways. First, Levi appears here as a named gate (v.31, north side) but received no land allotment. In the Mosaic arrangement, Levi's portion was the LORD Himself — no territorial inheritance (Num 18:20). In the restoration vision, Levi retains its unique status: no land portion, but a named gate into God's city. The tribe defined by its proximity to the sanctuary has a gate but not a field. This is not diminishment; it is continuation of Levi's distinctive identity. Second, Joseph appears as a single gate (v.32, east side) rather than Ephraim and Manasseh separately, compressing the Joseph half-tribes back to their father's name so that Levi can appear without exceeding twelve gates.\n\nThe symmetry of three gates per side, twelve total, is not merely aesthetic. In the ancient Near East, the city gate was the primary site of civic life — courts were held there, commerce transacted, elders met, proclamations made (Ruth 4:1-2; Prov 31:23; Amos 5:15). To have a named gate is to have a constituted place in the city's public life. Every tribe has a gate. No tribe presents itself at the city's wall only to find its name absent. The gate-list is the architectural form of the allotment-list's equity theology: every member of the covenant community has both land and access.\n\nJohn sees this structure from across the canon. Revelation 21:12-13 describes the new Jerusalem with twelve gates named for the twelve tribes of Israel, three on each side, in exactly the same arrangement as Ezekiel 48:31-34. John is working explicitly in Ezekiel's tradition, reading the prophet's vision as finding its ultimate fulfillment in the eternal city of the new creation. Whether one reads Ezekiel 48 as millennial blueprint or eschatological type, the canonical connection to Revelation 21-22 is exegetically undeniable — the same God, the same promise, the same twelve names, the same city."
